itus (T2DM) pathology. Despite Metformin intervention, the HbA1c remains at the diagnostic threshold, suggesting mitochondrial inefficiency and suboptimal glucose disposal in skeletal muscle.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## 14.3 Cross-Axis Interactions and Root Cause Mapping\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### The Axis 1-3 Feed-Forward Loop (Meta-inflammation)\\\\\\\\nIn the case of Mr. Somchai, the interaction between Inflammation and Metabolic axes creates a deleterious cycle:\\\\\\\\n1.  **Metabolic Overload (Axis 3):** Elevated glycemic indices lead to the formation of Advanced Glycation End-products (AGEs).\\\\\\\\n2.  **Inflammatory Activation (Axis 1):** AGEs bind to their receptors (RAGE), activating NF-kB pathways, which further elevate CRP levels.\\\\\\\\n3.  **Insulin Resistance Amplification:** Chronic inflammatory signaling impairs insulin receptor substrate (IRS-1) phosphorylation, worsening glucose control (Axis 3 feedback).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Symptom-Axis Mapping\\\\\\\\n*   **Fatigue (Afternoon):** Likely secondary to post-prandial glycemic excursions and mitochondrial oxidative stress within Axis 3.\\\\\\\\n*   **Insomnia:** Reflects a disruption in the HPA-axis (Axis 2 - Neuro-Endocrine), often triggered by nocturnal hypoglycemia or inflammatory cytokine spikes (IL-1, TNF) affecting the circadian rhythm.\\\\\\\\n*   **Bloating:** Potential Gut-Microbiome Axis involvement (Axis 5), where dysbiosis serves as the trigger for the systemic inflammation seen in Axis 1.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## 14.4 Clinical Synthesis and Omics Integration\\\\\\\\nThe 'Root Cause' is identified as a failure in Metabolic Homeostasis (Axis 3) acting as a primary driver for Inflammatory Upregulation (Axis 1). To stabilize the system, interventions must move beyond glucose lowering (Metformin) to include immunomodulatory strategies that address the systemic CRP elevation, thereby breaking the cycle of meta-inflammation.\\\"}\",\"metadata\":{\"thoughtSignature\":\"\"}}],\"metadata\":{\"generate\":{\"outpu